erary imagination as it was an achievement of medical Enlightenment science. Wang traces our modern pandemic-era crisis of vaccine hesitancy back to Edward Jenner’s publication of his treatise on vaccination in 1798, the first rumblings of an anti-vaccination movement, and vaccination’s formative literary history that included authors such as William Wordsworth, William Blake, John Keats, Mary Shelley, and Arthur Conan Doyle. The book concludes with a re-examination of the current deeply contentious public discourse about vaccines that has arisen in the wake of the COVID-19 pandemic. By recovering the surprisingly literary genres of Romantic-era medical writing, The Smallpox Report models a new literary historical perspective on our own crises of vaccine refusal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiseases in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and medicinezEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aMedicine in literature. 0aRomanticismzEngland. 0aSmallpox in literature. 0aVaccination in literature. 0aVaccinationzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  aArthur Conan Doyle.  aCOVID.  aDarwin.  aEdward Jenner.  aJohn Keats.  aMary Shelley.  aRomantic literature.  aWilliam Blake.  aWilliam Wordsworth.  aanti-vaccination.  aepidemics.  aillness narrative.  apandemic.  asmallpox.  avaccination.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754662540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487546625423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487546625/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  U